title: For Sale/Trade:   Rare First Model 1894 Iver Johnson Top-Break External Hammer 32 Cal.
postcontent:
This is a rare Iver Johnson Top Break External Hammer Model 1, First Model chambered for the .32 cal. with Single top latch, manufactured in 1894, early serial number is 3052 (no letter prefix). Marked on the top of the barrel rib is very rare: IVER JOHNSON'S ARMS & CYCLE WORKS FITCHBURG. MASS.U.S.A. "Only". It does not include the following PAT'D.APR.6.86.FEB.15.87.MAY 10.87.DEC.26.93 PAT'S PENDING, as with others you will find. I have never seen another First Model missing the Pat's Pending on the barrel. The caliber is also missing on the barrel. The bluing is surprisingly good considering the age of the pistol, although part of the cylinder has lost its bluing. The action (cylinder) is tight and works perfectly. The latch is tight and locks barrel to the frame, and the bore is Excellent. 
Additional info:
Iver Johnson nomenclature refers to its top-break revolvers as Safety Automatics. These are revolvers, not semi-automatic pistols. The term “Safety Automatic” refers to Iver Johnson’s transfer bar safety system (“safety”) and the automatic ejection of cartridges upon breaking open the revolvers (“automatic”).

Safety automatic
Standard models with external hammer:

First Model (1894–1895), single post latch system
Second Model (1896–1908), double post latch system
Third Model (1909–1941), double post latch system, adapted for smokeless powder
You need to know what model it is, 1st and 2nd models are black powder ONLY. 3rd models can take smokeless.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Mini-14 with underfolder stock
postcontent:
VERY LOW serial number 181-series Mini-14.

Compact, robust, lightweight, low-recoil zombie killer.  A conversation starter at the range.

100% functionality, 85-90% cosmetics.

Not a single FTFire, FTFeed, or FTEject in the 200 rounds I've put through it.

I called Ruger's customer service department to confirm the vintage - it's a first-year 181 series from 1977.  This is the lowest serial# 181-series I've ever encountered.  Highly desirable!!  It was produced before Ruger added the safety warning script on the left-side of the receiver, which, on 1978 and later models reads "BEFORE USING GUN -READ WARNINGS IN INSTRUCTION MANUAL AVAILABLE FREE FROM" ... above the Sturm, Ruger & Co. marks.

Apparently, Ruger's lawyers watched "A Christmas Story" and became worried about other Ralphie's 'shooting their eye out'.  ;)

It appears to have under 1,000 rounds through it...  The gas pipe showed a little erosion, so I went ahead and replaced it with a new factory Ruger SS gas pipe.  [My dad's 1978 Mini clocked about 3200-3300 rounds through it before it began ejecting the brass too softly] ... A fresh Mini kicks brass a good 15 feet out; my dad's began ejecting them about 2-3 feet, and another magazine later, was essentially a single-shot rifle.  NOT a great zombie gun.  I replaced his gas pipe [a whopping $8 part] and now his Mini functions flawlessly.

FYI: if you own a Mini, do yourself a favor and pick up a spare gas pipe or two before SHTF.  It's basically the only consumable part on these fine weapons.

I replaced the wood handguard with a RamLine plastic one...  nobody likes getting bit by the slide.  I installed a new factory Ruger slide stop cover plate also, the previous owner had one of those stupid scope mounts on it - total garbage.  If you plan on equipping a non-Ranch Rifle Mini-14/30 with optics, go with a rail from Omega, etc.

The best thing about my Mini-14 is the underfolding stock, a terrific piece made by Federal Ordnance back in the 1980's for LE use.  I have seen these stocks sell for $300+ in mint shape.

Certainly my underfolder saw some wear & tear before I purchased it...  It was the previous owner's "Truck Gun"... and I bought it for the same reason - it's no safe queen!  Just a dead-simple proven design that goes 'bang' every single time you pull the trigger.  It likes 55-grain ammo fine, but it prints even tighter groups with 40-grain polymer tip varmint bullets.

Otherwise, it's bone-stock.  Iron sights.

I will include two Tapco Gen2 polymer 30-round magazines in FDE.  They run sweet and have an anti-tilt follower.  Also, a metal 20-rounder, which the stock CAN fold/unfold around.

$700 cash only, no trades, no low-ballers.  Price is rock-bottom and a killer deal.

Face-to-face only, buyer must present valid Oregon DL or CHL so I don't have any liability.

Prefer not to sell or trade off ammo until rifle is gone, but might consider it, depending on what the offer is, just let me know the deal.
